. Nonprofits and the Environment: Using Market Forces for Social Good -- t16. The Outcomes Movement in Philanthropy and the Nonprofit Sector -- tPart V. Balancing Access and Inclusion -- tIntroduction -- t17. Charitable Nonprofits and the Business of Health Care -- t18. Education and the Nonprofit Sector: Schools and Organizational Intermediaries -- t19. Nonprofit Arts Organizations: Sustainability and Rationales for Support -- tPart VI. Advocacy, Engagement, and the Public -- tIntroduction -- t20. Advocacy, Civic Engagement, and Social Change -- t21. The Changing Face of Nonprofit Advocacy: Democratizing Potentials and Risks in an Unequal Context -- t22. Advocating for What? The Nonprofit Press and Models of the Public -- tPart VII. Motivation, Meaning, and Prosocial Behavior -- tIntroduction -- t23. What Influences Charitable Giving? -- t24. The Altruism Budget: Measuring and Encouraging Charitable Giving -- t25. What Do Volunteers Do? -- t26. Religious Organizations: Crosscutting the Nonprofit Sector -- tPart VIII. Global and Comparative Perspectives -- tIntroduction -- t27. The Global Rise of Nongovernmental Organizations -- t28. Global Backlash against Foreign Funding to Domestic Nongovernmental Organizations -- t29. Social Movements in a Global Context: History, Content, and Form -- t30. Comparative Nonprofit Sector Research: A Critical Assessment -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe nonprofit sector has changed in fundamental ways in recent decades. As the sector has grown in scope and size, both domestically and internationally, the boundaries between for-profit, governmental, and charitable organizations have become intertwined. Nonprofits are increasingly challenged on their roles in mitigating or exacerbating inequality. And debates flare over the role of voluntary organizations in democratic and autocratic societies alike. The Nonprofit Sector takes up these concerns and offers a cutting-edge empirical and theoretical assessment of the state of the field. This book, now in its third edition, brings together leading researchers—economists, historians, philosophers, political scientists, and sociologists along with scholars from communication, education, law, management, and policy schools—to investigate the impact of associational life. Chapters consider the history of the nonprofit sector and of philanthropy; the politics of the public sphere; governance, mission, and engagement; access and inclusion; and global perspectives on nonprofit organizations. Across this comprehensive range of topics, The Nonprofit Sector makes an essential contribution to the study of civil society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCharitable uses, trusts, and foundations. 0aNonprofit organizationsxManagement. 0aNonprofit organizations. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Philanthropy & Charity.2bisacsh1 aAnanny, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnheier, Helmut K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArum, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloemraad, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandtner, Christof, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrest, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBringel, Breno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBromley, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBromley, Patricia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrown, Maoz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClemens, Elisabet